```java
/**
 * This program demonstrates custom power calculations without using built-in methods.
 * It displays a table of integers from 1 to 10 along with their squares, cubes, and fourth powers.
 */
public class PowerTable {

    /**
     * Calculates the power of a base raised to an exponent using iterative multiplication.
     * 
     * @param base The number to be raised to a power
     * @param exponent The power to raise the base to (must be non-negative)
     * @return The result of base raised to the exponent
     */
    public static long calculatePower(int base, int exponent) {
        long result = 1;
        // Multiply the base by itself 'exponent' times
        for (int i = 0; i < exponent; i++) {
            result *= base;
        }
        return result;
    }

    /**
     * Main method that generates and displays the power table.
     * 
     * @param args Command line arguments (not used)
     */
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Print table header
        System.out.println("Number\tSquare\tCube\tFourth Power");
        System.out.println("------\t------\t----\t------------");

        // Generate and display the table rows
        for (int num = 1; num <= 10; num++) {
            // Calculate powers using our custom method
            long square = calculatePower(num, 2);
            long cube = calculatePower(num, 3);
            long fourthPower = calculatePower(num, 4);

            // Display the results in a formatted table row
            System.out.printf("%d\t%d\t%d\t%d%n", num, square, cube, fourthPower);
        }
    }
}
```

### Explanation:

